4) Place the remaining piece through the middle of the spool and set into the notches on the uprights.

description.text:
My practice of reaction-diffusion model.
The reaction-diffusion system is a model to generate pattern of surface of some animals (such as zebra or fish). Nice explanation here: http://www.karlsims.com/rd.html .
Calculated cubic world with C program, place around cube with OpenSCAD program.

Printer:

Da Vinci 2.0 Duo

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Notes: To change reaction-diffusion pattern (various parameters of reaction-diffusion, random seed, resolution, # of iteration), edit "rdcube.c", compile and run, redirect output to "rddube-sub.scad". The algorithm is Gray-Scott model on cube world (each face is made with matrix, which continues at the edge with the next face).
  • Currently the C program is too dirty (complex), and I don't upload.
    • To change design of the cube, change "rdcube.scad". I made it to consist a manifold object, but OpenSCAD itself or other CAD software says it's not a manifold... (I don't know the reason.) I fixed it with Meshmixer, then Microsoft Model Repair service. The "rdcube-sub.scad" is a part of OpenSCAD program, which initializes array v[] with the data. I don't have texture mapping (zmap) skill/software to place matrix onto surface, so did this way. Please comment better ways.

I used different three C programs (not shown here) to calculate reaction-diffusion system, which made output as OpenSCAD array v[] initializer sub program, then render with OpenSCAD.  Calculation mesh is 40 x 40 for each face, object size is scaled to 40 x 40 x 40 mm.
The world has no end like torus, but it's interesting that edges seems to have singularity, and the pattern aligns parallel/vertical to edges.
The rdcube2 is made with smaller "diffusion rate" F, then calculate difference with smaller cube using Blender.  The difference (outer pattern) is for black filament, inner cube for white filament, to print out with dual color 3D printer.
On the rdcube3, the kill ratio k varies between one corner to opposite corner.  Then calculate difference (outer, white) and union (inner, black) with smaller cube, print out with dual color.

description.text: @ustkl created a great model of a 1:1 lego character with all the individual parts.  Not an easy print, but not impossible at all.  The kids in my family loved it.  Then I found @jendaviswilson model that was a single piece 1:1 lego Clone Trooper.  I decided remix the two models so that we could have the helmet and torso of the trooper to print and fit on a regular lego character or the fully printed character.  First print came out great.  Everything moves just like the real thing. 10 pieces total.  Pics above show it next to a real one.  The detail on both the helmet and torso came out great.  I may lower the helmet a bit later, but not bad.  I now want to put some paint and clear coat on it.  Hopefully others will do some remixes with other character accessories.  The precision of new printers make it possible to get this small with detail.  I use a Robo 3D R1+ and love the outcomes.

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1 mm (100 micron) or finer

100%

Notes: Print first layer slow. I did 15mm/sec to make sure the small bits stick and lay well. From there I kept is slower than normal prints at around 40 mm/sec. Set it to .3 mm first layer and .1 mm from there. This was done in Hatchbox PLA at 200 C hotend and 50 C bed temp. I used Cura 15.4 with support for baseplate for the helmet, but it added it to the head and torso. All came off super easy with a needle nose pliers.

Some cleanup was needed.  I took a 3/16 drill bit by hand (without drill) to clean up the top hole of the helmet and then took a 3/8 bit with a small piece of 100 grit sandpaper wrapped onto the end to do a little cleanup of the interior of the helmet to fit smoothly.  Need to also take a hobby knife to cut off the built in support.  Might need a small file to clean up here and there.  I would recommend clear coating.  I want to put some paint on it as well.

This is my first practical design for a printable desk lamp. The lamp has 2 separate parts: the base and the shade. The base holds the light source which is a standard 68mm/2.75" diameter LED "puck" light that is powered by 3 AAA batteries. I bought 3 of these lights at Lowes for $9.98 batteries included. The photos show the lamp base with the puck, the lamp lit in a totally dark room sitting on a grey bedspread, and the lamp on my desk both lit and unlit. Here is a link to the puck light: http://www.lowes.com/pd_406110-43768-NS511-R6-306_1z0y4gqZ1z10d2u__?productId=4177463&pl=1 I originally designed the base to hold some sort of wall-powered light (I found a very cool color-changing LED lamp that has a nifty remote control), so it allowed for a space through which the power cord could pass. But I was unable to find a socket that fit the base, so I substituted the LED puck light instead. With this design you actually don't need the base at all - the shade can sit right on a table top with the light inside it if you prefer. I do plan on redesigning the base by giving it a more organic shape that better suits the overall shade design. The base for this design prints in about 3 hours, and the shade requires about 7 hours. I used a 0.200 mm layer height for both parts. Note that the shade presents only a small surface area in contact with the print bed, so it is necessary to use a brim when printing. For my print I used a brim of 6 loops, with each loop = 0.400 mm. My next design will feature this same shade but with twisted ribs on the outside. Edit: lampbase-round.stl is a simpler base that is easier and quicker to print.

This makes it easy to remove the HeatBed element and still have the cablechain attached to the Y-carriage. The Case side of the cablechain is attached to a stainrelif. This can be mounted left or right depending of board used. This side of the cablechain has soldered cableends and a 3pin thermistor connector and is epoxi glued in the caseblock. This project focuses on a redesign of the 450 frame from DJI to include a lot of improvements.
It is designed to fit a PixHawk Flight Controller, mounted on an embedded dumper board included in the new upper board of the F450 Shell.
A high resistant cover is designed to protect the flight controller inspired in the DJI Inspire designs. All the additional electronics are included under the shell cover with enough access to manipulate them on the field.
The model is designed to fit a GPS, a Buzzer, an external Led&USB board, the security switch, 3dr telemetry, receiver and all the cables.
In the future I will design some type of lateral cover with ease disposal to protect the electronic from dust and lateral hazards ;) The bottom plate also includes some improvements. First of all, it includes a battery barrier to help insert and maintain the battery on place (size of a 2200 3S). These vertical barriers also offer more strength to the design.
It also includes some specially designed holes to attach a 32GB Gimbal plate with 4 damper balls.
Finally, the projects include a redesign of a very famous gimbal design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:262809) to fit on the bottom of the Quad. This gimbal is designed to snap a Mobius Cam, but the arm of the gimbal, make very difficult to access to power button of the camera, so I redesigned it to make it easier to operate it.
To enable the attachment of the gimbal, it is necessary to include 4 legs. The included legs are not my design, but I cannot remember where I grabbed them.
The legs provided in this model are no tall enough to land with the gimbal attached, so be aware to include some extra-large legs on the model (I will redesign them in the future). All the work has been done with the (extremely easy to use) tool Tinker Cad, Which I clearly recommend. You can access the project freely here: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/gnYhNaWjS5L-pixhawk-cover-dji-f450-pixhawk-improvements-v2/edit Hope you enjoy it as much as I have done during the design and creation process ;)

I have just uploaded a standard and large version of the legs and a small modification of the gimbal design just to enable access the buttoms of the mobius.
Just take not two thing: first the design are not mine, I have just modified them to fit my needs.
Second, the standard legs do not have length enough to fit the gimball. You will need the extended ones. If you need to modify them, just grab from the tinkercad link

Push puppets are around as long as I can remember and I've always loved the simple yet smart, funny and inspiring little toys.

title: Heavy duty filament spool - for mendel

description.text:
Remixed with http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10254 (spindle for Randyy's spool), and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11250 (one piece printable arms) to adapt it for the RepRap. It's not very different from the original model, but I spend many hours in Sketchup tweaking it : correcting the scale in mm, getting rid of many mesh problems (face orientations and holes, especially in the hub), lower the height of the hub and the arms, join the arms in one piece like Fil did with the Randyy's ones, fuse the RotoScan's clip with the Tjhowse's spindle, organize the parts to be production friendly for a Mendel bed.
And finally present the whole in a "new thing" to make less works for the other who want to print that spool for their RepRap :) For me it printed good, hub and spindle are maybe tight to clip at first but can spin freely after some movements, sometimes the dovetails can require a little sanding but its a really nice spool, thanks RotoScan ! (video of spinning : http://youtu.be/9SCrJz4pWRs)

As say RotoScan : "Print out and assemble. The dovetail parts should not need any trimming except for part that lies against the build platform. Even so, if you assemble it when it is warm you may not even need to do that. Wind the filament onto the spool. Start by threading the filament through the holes on the "U" shaped parts. Wind the filament so that it just lies gently in place. When you have finished loading the spool, cut the filament and then press the end of the filament into the built-in clips to keep it from unraveling." Hang the spindle on the top bars of your Mendel and clip the spool (I have one spool per color and just swap-clip between them). Alternatively you can print these double-fork http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:12273 if you want to hold two coils on the same spool. Next : add this filament guide http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11521 and you will be fine for the feeding :)

description.text: So here are the 3d parts needed to create an Acrylic or Polycarbonate (for higher temp resistance) print area enclosure. I wanted an enclosure which can keep the heat in for ABS printing, keep dust out and as much of the electronics out. I also wanted this to be doable by all enthusiasts not just once with garages and powerful tools. Yes it's easy and much easier to put the whole thing in a box but for me keeping the electronics cool is very important as it ensures good performance. Plus it looks cool. For a full set of instructions on how to assemble and what you need please head over to: http://www.gi-architects.co.uk/2015/12/prusa-i3-print-encloser/. It was just too much to put all in here. Update 1: I have included the 123dx file and a step(.stp) export.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

40%

Notes: You only need supports if the screw holes don't come out correctly. I would suggest that you print 4 objects at a time (same type), it's what i did and come out perfectly fine. You can use slicer to split them.

I did have to enlarge the holes a tiny bit after printing as i used ABS which tends to shrink a tiny bit (the drawings are exact for m3 bolts). Other than that i sanded them a tiny bit and painted them.
The upper left part holding the back enclosure has a flat surface where you can glue or drill and anchor the screen.

I store my espresso tamper on top of the convenient flat surface of the "doser" of my Rancilio coffee grinder. Unfortunately, the vibration of the grinder often caused the heavy tamper to move and eventually fall (loudly!) to the counter top. 
I created this ring to store the tamper so this doesn't happen any more. Works great!
My tamper is 2 9/32-inch (about 58 mm) in diameter. The hole in the retainer ring is 61 mm, which leaves so wiggle room. I included the OpenSCAD file if you want to adjust the size for your different size tampers.
The screw holes were intentionally left small. I drilled them out to fit self-tapping screws for attaching to the lid. You could also glue the ring to the lid if you prefer.

description.text:
This is a 2 axis brushless gimbal mount for a small HD camera. I wanted something small and self contained to mess around with. Some sample video can be found here:
http://youtu.be/E7JgD8KLPkc I should probably rubber mount the camera next time. It was just clamped directly onto the tank. As you can see, when the motorcycle leans, the image stays reasonably level. Performance can be improved with better PID tweaking I am sure. equipment used:
Gimbal controller and sensor: http://www.foxtechfpv.com/aio-brushless-gimbal-controller-p-1095.html motors:
http://www.foxtechfpv.com/foxtech-bgm220870-brushless-gimbal-motor-p-1074.html camera: Boscam HD19 ExplorerHD http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__32024__Boscam_HD19_ExplorerHD_Full_HD_1080p_FPV_Video_Camera_with_Integral_Recorder.html the battery is just an old 3s 1600 lipo pack I had laying around... the current requirements are pretty low and I can power the controller and camera directly from the 12.6V battery. while this works fairly well, I will probably redesign it with a slip ring to manage the wires a little more cleanly.

print fairly solid for strength. I used supports to keep the dimensional accuracy. Make sure you balance the roll arm with lead weights to counter the weight of the motor hanging off one side. The tilt and roll axes should line up with the camera sensor  
The camera just snaps in place. No screws are required. the mounting tabs fit directly into the holes in the camera mount.  
The handle can obviously be printed fairly hollow (I did 20%)
